Groups.common_instructions: It is not luck but labour that makes man. Luck, says an American writer, is ever waiting for something to turn up; labour with keen eyes and strong will always turn up something. Luck lies in bed and wishes that the postman would bring him news of a legacy; labour turns out at six and with busy pen and ringing hammer lays the foundation of competence. Luck whines, labour watches. Luck relies on chance, labour on character. Luck slips downwards to self-indulgence; labour strides upwards and aspires to independence. The conviction therefore is, extending that; diligence is the mother of good luck. In other words that, a man's success in life will be proportionate to his efforts, to his industriousness, to his attention to small things.

Which of the following statements are true for page fault?
ExamQuestions.OptionA: A page fault (sometimes #pf or pf) is a trap to the software raised by the hardware when a program accesses a page that is mapped in the virtual address space, but not loaded in physical memory.
ExamQuestions.OptionB: The hardware that detects a page fault is the MMU in a processor.
ExamQuestions.OptionC: If the page is loaded in memory at the time the fault is generated, but is not marked in the MMU as being loaded in memory, then it is called an Invalid page fault.
ExamQuestions.OptionD: If a page fault occurs for a reference to an address that's not part of the virtual address space, so that there can't be a page in memory corresponding to it, then it is called a Major page fault.

ExamQuestions.OptionA: Switching the CPU to another Process requires saving the state of the old process and loading the new process state. This is called Context Switch.
ExamQuestions.OptionB: A critical region is a piece of code that only a finite number of processes execute.

ExamQuestions.Question: Which of the following functions is/are performed by the loader?
ExamQuestions.OptionA: Allocate space in memory for the programs and resolve symbolic references between object decks.

ExamQuestions.OptionC: Resolve references to external symbols, assign final addresses to procedures/functions and variables, and revises code and data to reflect new addresses (a process called relocation).
ExamQuestions.OptionD: Physically places the machine instructions and data into memory.
